     9â†’
    10â†’> **Note**: As of Go 1.20, the standard library provides [`errors.Join`](https://pkg.go.dev/errors#Join) which offers similar functionality for combining multiple errors. **For new projects, we recommend using `errors.Join` from the standard library.** This package provides additional features like custom formatting, the `Group` pattern for concurrent error collection, and utility functions (`Append`, `Flatten`, `Prefix`).
    11â†’
    12â†’## Migrating to `errors.Join`
    13â†’
    14â†’**Basic error aggregation:**
    15â†’```go
    16â†’// Before (go-multierror)
    17â†’var result error
    18â†’result = multierror.Append(result, err1)
    19â†’result = multierror.Append(result, err2)
    20â†’return result
    21â†’
    22â†’// After (stdlib)
    23â†’var errs []error
    24â†’if err1 != nil {
    25â†’    errs = append(errs, err1)
    26â†’}
    27â†’if err2 != nil {
    28â†’    errs = append(errs, err2)
    29â†’}
    30â†’if len(errs) > 0 {
    31â†’    return errors.Join(errs...)
    32â†’}
    33â†’return nil
    34â†’```
    35â†’
    36â†’**Custom formatting:**
    37â†’```go
    38â†’// go-multierror allows custom formatting
    39â†’// With stdlib, wrap the joined error with a custom type if needed
    40â†’type FormattedError struct {
    41â†’    errs []error
    42â†’}
    43â†’
    44â†’func (e *FormattedError) Error() string {
    45â†’    // Your custom format here
    46â†’    return fmt.Sprintf("multiple errors: %v", e.errs)
    47â†’}
    48â†’
    49â†’func (e *FormattedError) Unwrap() []error {
    50â†’    return e.errs
    51â†’}
    52â†’```
    53â†’
    54â†’**Concurrent error collection (Group):**
    55â†’```go
    56â†’// golang.org/x/sync/errgroup returns only the first error:
    57â†’import "golang.org/x/sync/errgroup"
    58â†’
    59â†’g := new(errgroup.Group)
    60â†’g.Go(func() error { return task1() })
    61â†’g.Go(func() error { return task2() })
    62â†’err := g.Wait() // Returns first error only
    63â†’
    64â†’// To collect ALL errors like multierror.Group does, use a mutex:
    65â†’type ErrorCollector struct {
    66â†’    mu   sync.Mutex
    67â†’    errs []error
    68â†’}
    69â†’
    70â†’func (ec *ErrorCollector) Add(err error) {
    71â†’    if err != nil {
    72â†’        ec.mu.Lock()
    73â†’        ec.errs = append(ec.errs, err)
    74â†’        ec.mu.Unlock()
    75â†’    }
    76â†’}
    77â†’
    78â†’func (ec *ErrorCollector) Err() error {
    79â†’    ec.mu.Lock()
    80â†’    defer ec.mu.Unlock()
    81â†’    if len(ec.errs) == 0 {
    82â†’        return nil
    83â†’    }
    84â†’    return errors.Join(ec.errs...)
    85â†’}
    86â†’```
    87â†’
    88â†’---
    89â†’
    90â†’`go-multierror` is a package for Go that provides a mechanism for
    91â†’representing a list of `error` values as a single `error`.
    92â†’
    93â†’This allows a function in Go to return an `error` that might actually
    94â†’be a list of errors. If the caller knows this, they can unwrap the
    95â†’list and access the errors. If the caller doesn't know, the error
    96â†’formats to a nice human-readable format.
    97â†’
    98â†’`go-multierror` is compatible with the Go standard library
    99â†’[errors](https://golang.org/pkg/errors/) package, supporting the
   100â†’`As`, `Is`, and `Unwrap` functions for error introspection. Note that `Unwrap` 
   101â†’returns errors one at a time via chaining, unlike `errors.Join` which 
   102â†’implements the newer `Unwrap() []error` signature (Go 1.20+).
   103â†’
   104â†’## Installation and Docs
   105â†’
   106â†’Install using `go get github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror`.
   107â†’
   108â†’Full documentation is available at
   109â†’https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror
   110â†’
   111â†’### Requires go version 1.13 or newer
   112â†’
   113â†’`go-multierror` requires go version 1.13 or newer. Go 1.13 introduced
   114â†’[error wrapping](https://golang.org/doc/go1.13#error_wrapping), which
   115â†’this library takes advantage of.
   116â†’
   117â†’If you need to use an earlier version of go, you can use the
   118â†’[v1.0.0](https://github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/tree/v1.0.0)
   119â†’tag, which doesn't rely on features in go 1.13.
   120â†’
   121â†’If you see compile errors that look like the below, it's likely that
   122â†’you're on an older version of go:
   123â†’
   124â†’```
   125â†’/go/src/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/multierror.go:112:9: undefined: errors.As
   126â†’/go/src/github.com/hashicorp/go-multierror/multierror.go:117:9: undefined: errors.Is
   127â†’```
   128â†’
   129â†’## Usage
   130â†’
   131â†’go-multierror is easy to use and purposely built to be unobtrusive in
   132â†’existing Go applications/libraries that may not be aware of it.
   133â†’
   134â†’**Building a list of errors**
   135â†’
   136â†’The `Append` function is used to create a list of errors. This function
   137â†’behaves a lot like the Go built-in `append` function: it doesn't matter
   138â†’if the first argument is nil, a `multierror.Error`, or any other `error`,
   139â†’the function behaves as you would expect.
   140â†’
   141â†’```go
   142â†’var result error
   143â†’
   144â†’if err := step1(); err != nil {
   145â†’	result = multierror.Append(result, err)
   146â†’}
   147â†’if err := step2(); err != nil {
   148â†’	result = multierror.Append(result, err)
   149â†’}
   150â†’
   151â†’return result
   152â†’```
   153â†’
   154â†’**Customizing the formatting of the errors**
   155â†’
   156â†’By specifying a custom `ErrorFormat`, you can customize the format
   157â†’of the `Error() string` function:
   158â†’
   159â†’```go
   160â†’var result *multierror.Error
   161â†’
   162â†’// ... accumulate errors here, maybe using Append
   163â†’
   164â†’if result != nil {
   165â†’	result.ErrorFormat = func([]error) string {
   166â†’		return "errors!"
   167â†’	}
   168â†’}
   169â†’```
   170â†’
   171â†’**Accessing the list of errors**
   172â†’
   173â†’`multierror.Error` implements `error` so if the caller doesn't know about
   174â†’multierror, it will work just fine. But if you're aware a multierror might
   175â†’be returned, you can use type switches to access the list of errors:
   176â†’
   177â†’```go
   178â†’if err := something(); err != nil {
   179â†’	if merr, ok := err.(*multierror.Error); ok {
   180â†’		// Use merr.Errors
   181â†’	}
   182â†’}
   183â†’```
   184â†’
   185â†’You can also use the standard [`errors.Unwrap`](https://golang.org/pkg/errors/#Unwrap)
   186â†’function. This will continue to unwrap into subsequent errors until none exist.
   187â†’
   188â†’**Extracting an error**
   189â†’
   190â†’The standard library [`errors.As`](https://golang.org/pkg/errors/#As)
   191â†’function can be used directly with a multierror to extract a specific error:
   192â†’
   193â†’```go
   194â†’// Assume err is a multierror value
   195â†’err := somefunc()
   196â†’
   197â†’// We want to know if "err" has a "RichErrorType" in it and extract it.
   198â†’var errRich RichErrorType
   199â†’if errors.As(err, &errRich) {
   200â†’	// It has it, and now errRich is populated.
   201â†’}
   202â†’```
   203â†’
   204â†’**Checking for an exact error value**
   205â†’
   206â†’Some errors are returned as exact errors such as the [`ErrNotExist`](https://golang.org/pkg/os/#pkg-variables)
   207â†’error in the `os` package. You can check if this error is present by using
   208â†’the standard [`errors.Is`](https://golang.org/pkg/errors/#Is) function.
   209â†’
   210â†’```go
   211â†’// Assume err is a multierror value
   212â†’err := somefunc()
   213â†’if errors.Is(err, os.ErrNotExist) {
   214â†’	// err contains os.ErrNotExist
   215â†’}
   216â†’```
   217â†’
   218â†’**Returning a multierror only if there are errors**
   219â†’
   220â†’If you build a `multierror.Error`, you can use the `ErrorOrNil` function
   221â†’to return an `error` implementation only if there are errors to return:
   222â†’
   223â†’```go
   224â†’var result *multierror.Error
   225â†’
   226â†’// ... accumulate errors here
   227â†’
   228â†’// Return the `error` only if errors were added to the multierror, otherwise
   229â†’// return nil since there are no errors.
   230â†’return result.ErrorOrNil()
   231â†’```
